03953nam a22006255i 9780292743649DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212013txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927436497 a10.7560/7436322doi  a(DE-B1597)588367  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aP115.2b.M37 2013eb 7aFOR0260002bisacsh1 aMarks, Stephen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBecoming a Bilingual Family :bHelp Your Kids Learn Spanish (and Learn Spanish Yourself in the Process) /cStephen Marks, Jeffrey Marks. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2013  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThe Journey to Bilingualism -- tA Phrase Book for Talking to Kids -- tA Quick Course in Spanish Pronunciation -- tGrammar Enough to Get You Started -- tSpanish Language Resources -- tKid Names in Spanish -- tIndex / Glossary0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWould you like your children to grow up bilingual, even if you aren’t yet? Then speak to your kids in Spanish as you learn the language along with them. Becoming a Bilingual Family gives English-speaking parents the tools to start speaking Spanish with their kids in their earliest years, when children are most receptive to learning languages. It teaches the vocabulary and idioms for speaking to children in Spanish and offers practical, proven ways to create a language-learning environment at home. The first part of the book introduces parents to many resources—books, audio books, music, television, computer programs, childcare workers, school, and friends—that can help you establish a home environment conducive to the acquisition of Spanish. The second part is a Spanish phrasebook that takes you through all the typical activities that parents and children share, from getting up in the morning to going to bed at night. Few, if any, other Spanish study aids provide this much vocabulary and guidance for talking to small children about common daily activities. The authors also include a quick course in Spanish pronunciation and enough grammar to get a parent started. Spanish-language resources, kids’ names in Spanish, and an easy-to-use index and glossary complete the book. Take the Markses’ advice and start talking to your kids in Spanish, even if it’s not perfect. You’ll learn the language together and share the excitement of discovering the peoples and cultures that make up the Spanish-speaking world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aBilingualism in children. 0aChildrenxLanguage. 0aParenting. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Spanish.2bisacsh1 aMarks, Jeffrey, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292743649423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292743649/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK